<TITLE> European shares shed 1 pct early after Fed </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares fell early on Wednesday led by banks as investors deemed the Federal Reserve's measures to ease monetary policy insufficient to battle the liquidity squeeze that is threatening broader economic growth. By 0810 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 1 percent at 1,525.22 points. Decliners outnumbered advancers by about 35 to 1. "The financial industry had expected the discount rate to be reduced by fifty basis points as money markets are still very stressed, showing mistrust is still the name of the game," said Heino Ruland, a strategist with FrankfurtFinanz. Rio Tinto was the largest weighted loser, falling 2.9 percent after saying it saw nothing new in comments from BHP Billiton that its proposed offer for Rio was still a compelling one. Among the banks, UBS, Royal Bank of Scotland and HBSC were down between 1.1 and 2.8 percent. U.S. benchmark indexes fell by as much as 2.5 percent on Tuesday after the Fed cut its target rate by an anticipated quarter-point to 4.25 percent. But the Fed did not deliver a steep cut to the discount rate that some investors had hoped for, as short-term borrowing rates linger near multi-year highs and threaten corporate access to cash. Around Europe, London's FTSE 100 index was down 1.2 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX lost 0.8 percent and Paris' CAC 40 fell 1.2 perce
